^d @e@2Regarding question by lisa about the "cue" bid, there is a general principle at work which I should @E@3explain. If an opponent makes an artificial bid that shows a certain suit or suits, and you then bid that suit, it is still a cue bid even though the opponent did not actually bid that suit. So, with the hand in question, the opponent bid 2NT. You can think of that as the opponent simultaneously bidding clubs and diamonds. Therefore, if you then bid clubs or diamonds yourself, that is not natural, it is still a cue bid. 

The auction 1@S-2N-3@C is essentially the same auction as 1@S-2@C-3@C. My only other point was that both 1@S-2N-3@C and 1@S-2N-3@D are both cue bids. However, an expert partnership might get sophisticated and give different meanings to each of those cue bidding auctions  (for example, 3@C is a limit raise, 3@D a forcing raise), but the essential point is 3@C and 3@D are both cue bids.

Another example of a cue bid after an artificial bid would be 1@S-2@S-3@H. Since the 2@S bidder is showing hearts (and a minor), 3@H is a cue bid showing a limit raise or better. The main difference in this auction is that, since the other minor is unspecified, a minor suit bid by responder is still natural, not a cue bid.

Now, let us resume our play.

